<HEAD>Senate Candidate Cautioned By Medical Board, Alleges GOP `Dirty
Trick'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kentucky's medical licensure board chided
Dr. Harvey Sloane, the Democratic nominee for U.S. Senate, for
writing prescriptions with an expired federal drug registration.
   But the board said Thursday no formal sanction was warranted.
Sloane said the inquiry into his writing prescription refills for
himself was ``a carefully orchestrated ... Republican dirty
trick.''
   A spokesman for Republican Sen. Mitch McConnell accused Sloane
of ``outrageous lies.''
   It was the second inquiry by the state Board of Medical
Licensure into Sloane's prescriptions.
   Last fall, the board advised Sloane to stop prescribing sleeping
pills for himself. Sloane, who no longer has an active medical
practice, said he wrote refills of the pills because of arthritis
pain in his hip and back pain from a degenerative disk disease. He
did not write the original prescriptions.
   The inquiry was prompted by the disclosure that Sloane's Drug
Enforcement Administration permit to write prescriptions had
expired in February 1987.
</TEXT>
