<HEAD>Rockefeller Ready to Unleash $1.6 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Sen. Jay Rockefeller has $1.6
million on hand for the remainder of his campaign against
Republican challenger John Yoder.
   The West Virginia Democrat already has outspent Yoder by a rate
of 47 to 1. Rockefeller has spent $917,293 compared with Yoder's
$19,338, according to financial records filed in connection with
the campaign.
   Rockefeller spent $11.7 million in 1980 to be re-elected
governor and $12.1 million in 1984 to be elected to the Senate,
both records for the state.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses Smith $300,000 For Election Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST CHESTER, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge denied an heir to the du Pont
fortune the $300,000 he requested from a trust to finance his
independent campaign for Congress.
   Thursday's denial by Anthony R. Appel, a Lancaster County judge
assigned to the case by the state Supreme Court, marks the second
such failure this week for Lewis du Pont Smith.
   Smith, 33, a follower of political extremist Lyndon LaRouche, is
running against Republican Rep. Richard Schulze, aneight-term
incumbent, and Democrat Sam Stretton, a West Chester attorney.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Rinfret Going Greyhound To Debate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican gubernatorial candidate Pierre
Rinfret says he will be going by Greyhound bus to the first
full-scale debate of the campaign.
   Rinfret, a millionaire Manhattan economist, says he is
demonstrating how strapped for money his campaign is.
   He will take the bus from New York City to Syracuse for the
Friday night debate.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Exon's Wife Says Drinking Allegations Have Hurt Family</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Jim Exon's wife says allegations that
her husband has a drinking problem have caused her family
considerable pain.
   ``It's hard on our children to hear things about their father
that they know aren't true,'' Pat Exon said at a fund-raising event
here for her husband, a two-term Democratic senator who is seeking
a third term against Republican Hal Daub.
   Mrs. Exon was referring to allegations former Sen. John Tower
made that Exon had a reputation as one of the heaviest drinkers in
the Senate. Tower made the comments during a campaign stop for Daub
in Nebraska last week.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Wilson Criticized For Campaign Contributions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmentalists called Republican
gubernatorial candidate Pete Wilson ``Pesticide Pete'' for
accepting $80,909 in campaign money from the pesticide industry.
   Wilson's campaign said the environmentalists were engaging in
smear tactics.
   The National Toxics Campaign said Wilson ranked third in the
U.S. Senate among recipients of pesticide industry contributions
between 1983 and 1988. The organization said Wilson ranked behind
Sen. Steve Simms, R-Idaho, and Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas.
   ``We had been wondering why Pete Wilson decided to oppose `Big
Green' (environmental initiative Proposition 128), and now we've
finally got an answer that makes sense,'' said Sierra Club member
Bob Hattoy.
   Wilson spokesman Otto Bos accused the National Toxics Campaign
of a ``big lie.'' He said Wilson was ranked ``third-best Republican
in the entire U.S. Senate on the environment by the national League
of Conservation Voters.... The voters are much smarter than to fall
for the `big lie,''' Bos said.
   He did not dispute, however, that Wilson received the
contributions.
</TEXT>
